I had a reasonable belief that there was a serious and imminent danger from Coronavirus at work, and that you were not taking reasonable steps to ensure the health and safety of employees. For example, [provide up to three bullet point examples, such as: 
-- I was asked to attend a workplace that was unsafe due to coronavirus; 
-- I could have worked from home, but was not allowed to; 
-- due to the number of people in the office it was impossible to maintain a safe distance between colleagues.]

As you'll be aware, you have a duty to protect the health and safety of your staff. A failure to comply with this duty may result in investigation by the Health and Safety Executive and a criminal prosecution.

The consultation is not meaningful because [insert your reasons for thinking that the consultation has not been not meaningful - for example: 
'You did not consult with me at all about the decision to make redundancies'; 
'Although you asked for my views on the redundancy situation, you completely ignored my suggestions so I do not consider it to have been a meaningful consultation'; 
'People have already been appointed to new roles prior to consultation’; 
'You have not responded to any of the points I raised during the consultation'.]

If a meaningful consultation were carried out I would not be made redundant because [List here any issues you could raise in a genuine consultation that might alter the decision to dismiss you.  See below for examples]. [Examples: 
'I could identify another role [name of role] that I am also qualified to carry out'; 
'I could tell you about an alternative way of funding my role.]

There is no genuine business reason for my redundancy. You are implementing the restructure in bad faith to remove me from the organisation because [Insert your reasons - see below for examples]]. [Examples: '
I am disabled and you do not want to make the required adjustments to enable me to carry out my role'; 
'I raised a grievance which was unfairly rejected and so you now wish to get rid of me'; 
'I told you about unlawful activities going on in the company and you do not want to deal with them'; 
'I am about to go on maternity leave and you wish to appoint someone permanently to carry out my duties'.]

I have not been consulted adequately about the redundancy and because of this [set out impact on you of lack of consultation - see below for examples]. [Examples: 
'I am not being given an opportunity to propose an alternative structure in which my role could remain’; 
'I am not being given the chance to raise the possibility of working part-time'; 
'If given the opportunity, I could identify the role of [name of role] in the organization that I am also qualified to carry out'; 
'I could suggest an alternative way of funding my role'.]

I am not being given the opportunity to apply for [insert name of role].  It would besuitable and I should be appointed to it because [Set out your reasons here.   See below for examples]. [Examples:  
'I have the skills necessary to undertake this role'; 
'I have already successfully carried out a similar role'; 
'the role is very similar to my role which is being made, or likely to be made, redundant.]

I applied for the alternative role of [insert name of role] but have been unsuccessful. I should be appointed to this role as it is a suitable alternative role for me. There is no reasonable basis why I am not being appointed because [Insert your reasons here - see below for examples]. [Examples: 
‘I have the skills necessary to undertake this role'; 
'I have already successfully carried out a similar role'; 
'the role is very similar to my role which is being made redundant’.]

There was no genuine business reason for my redundancy.  You were implementing the restructure in bad faith to remove me from the organisation because [set out the reasons]. 
[Examples of reasons: 'I am disabled and you did not want to make the required adjustments to enable me to carry out my role'; 
'I raised a grievance which was unfairly rejected and so you wanted to get rid of me'; 
'I told you about unlawful activities going on in the company and you did not want to deal with them'; 
'I was about to go on maternity leave and you wished to appoint someone permanently to carry out my duties'.]

You did not score me fairly in the selection process. If I had been scored fairly I would not have been selected. My evidence for this includes the following: [Insert your reasons here, for example:: 
'I was scored a 4 for Performance when all my appraisals were at least 6 for this criterion'; 
'My manager scored me lower than he should because he did not like me and these scores were not justified'; 
'I was on maternity leave for the last year and my previous year's performance was not taken into account'; 
'The work I did on [insert job/task details] was not taken into account.']

I was not consulted about the redundancy and because of this: [set out impact on you of lack of consultation, for example: 
'I was not given an opportunity to propose an alternative structure in which my role could have remained’; 
'I was not given the chance to raise the possibility of working part-time'; 
'If given the opportunity, I could have identified the role of [name of role] in the organization that I was also qualified to carry out'; 
'I could have suggested an alternative way of funding my role'.]

The consultation was not meaningful for the following reasons: [Insert your arguments for thinking that the consultation was not meaningful, for example: 
'People had already been appointed to new roles prior to consultation’; 
'You did not respond to any of the points I raised during the consultation'].

If a meaningful consultation had been carried out I would not have been made redundant because: [Here list any issues you could have raised in a genuine consultation that might have altered the decision to dismiss you. For example: 
'I could have identified another role [name of role] that I was also qualified to carry out'; 
'I could have told you about an alternative way of funding my role.]
